  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Listing Installed Packages**\n\nI\'ve just finished reviewing the installed packages. It seems the project utilizes Google\'s Generative AI, TailwindCSS, Vite for React, dotenv for environment variables, Express for the backend, Lucide React for icons, and Motion for animation. I\'m noting the specific versions for each.\n\n\n**Analyzing App\'s Foundation**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the foundational aspects. I see React version 19.0.1 and Vite 6.2.3. The app is a React application, a user-facing EV savings and activity tool called \"Volt.\" I\'ve begun reviewing the screens, starting with the Activity, Dashboard, Vehicle Details, Log Charging, and Add Your Vehicle screens. I\'m focusing on the user interface and functionality based on the provided images.\n\n\n**Detailing Key App Features**\n\nI\'m now diving into the specifics of the app\'s key features. I\'m focusing on the \"Volt\" app\'s core screens: the Dashboard and Activity pages. I\'m noting the details of the hero cards, quick metrics, interactive savings charts, and activity timelines for each page. I\'m also examining the two vehicle detail screens, particularly the MG Comet EV and Tata Nexon EV, which will follow similar patterns.\n\n\n**Exploring Vehicle Data**\n\nI\'m now detailing the \"Vehicles Page.\" I\'m noting that the main feature is a list of added vehicles, with an \"Add Your Vehicle\" option if the list is empty. The \"Add Your Vehicle\" wizard uses a search, brand buttons, and a manual entry option. I\'m also reviewing the \"Vehicle Details\" screen for the Tesla Model 3, Tata Nexon EV, and MG Comet EV, specifically focusing on the synced status, image showcase, and charging session details. This involves both the UI elements and the expected functionality.\n\n\n**Reviewing UI Components**\n\nI\'m now closely examining the image assets, focusing on UI elements. I\'m noting specific visuals, such as the side view of the Tata Nexon EV and the MG Comet EV images, which will be instrumental in understanding the visual representation of vehicles within the app\'s interfaces. I\'m focusing on layout to understand how images will be displayed.\n\n\n**Examining Image References**\n\nI\'m now carefully examining the image URLs provided, especially the avatar and vehicle detail screen sources. I\'m focusing on discrepancies and confirming the correct image sources in relation to user requests. It\'s important to cross-reference these for data validation.\n\n\n**Validating Image URLs**\n\nI\'m now cross-referencing the image URLs to confirm their integrity. I\'m focusing on the \"MG Comet EV\" and avatar images, paying close attention to any discrepancies. Validating the sources is crucial to avoid any potential errors in data representation or UI rendering. I\'m checking for variations or broken links.\n\n\n**Confirming Image Integrity**\n\nI\'m now carefully checking the images and URLs. I\'m confirming that the provided URLs correspond to the assets. The avatars seem professional, and I\'m cross-referencing to ensure image consistency and proper integration within the \"Volt\" application. The white SUV image is present. I\'m focusing on validating the sources.\n\n\n\n**Defining App Core Features**\n\nI\'m now detailing the \"Volt\" app\'s settings and interactive features. I\'m focusing on customizable settings like cost assumptions and profile parameters. I\'m also examining dynamic calculations for lifetime savings, petrol avoided, and CO2 reduction based on logs and input. Dynamic additions of charging sessions with instant updates are important. I am also planning how to make it user-friendly by adding and customizing the active vehicle. The interactive charts will also use custom timeline toggles. I plan to initialize the application metadata with a title \"Volt\" and description.\n\n\n"
